So let's start by drawing a diagram.<br> Everywhere point of contact touches the inscribed circle and the purple lines all go through the center of the inscribed circle and point of contact points are equidistant to each other. This means that the triangles are 30-60-90 triangles, we can start solving using this information.<br> So if we draw the purple line, and chase the distances starts to click, starting with the smallest distance from the edge of the purple line to the center of the purple circle. Since the small circle is the radius, it is immediately known that the entire length is a radius plus the small radius. If you observe of the triangle, the smaller radius makes a diameter just take half of the radius and you get <math>\frac{1}{2}</math>, that entire length adds up to <math>\frac{3}{2}</math>.<br> Doing this similarly for the other two small triangles we get <math>\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}</math>.<br> Now we know that the total radius of the inscribed circle is the sum of the red dotted line and the purple dotted line. Since both of these lengths are known, we must add them up and we get our answer. That is, in our terms, <math>\frac{1}{2}+\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}=\boxed{\frac{3+3\sqrt{3}}{2}}</math>.


